======================================================================
FIBONACCI TILING & GALOIS SPLITTING — opus-2026-03-12-S67d
======================================================================

PART 1: FIBONACCI AS TILING COUNT — CAN WE TILE TOURNAMENTS?
======================================================================

F_n = number of tilings of 1×(n-1) strip with squares and dominoes
F_p = prod(1+Q_k) for the Interval tournament on p vertices

QUESTION: Is there a tiling model on the tournament where:
  - Each tiling has weight 1
  - Total count = prod(1+Q_k)?

Transfer matrix comparison:
  Fibonacci:    T_F = [[1,1],[1,0]], eigenvalues φ, ψ = (1±√5)/2
  Morgan-Voyce: T_B = [[3,-1],[1,0]], eigenvalues φ², ψ²

KEY: T_B = T_F², i.e., the MV transfer matrix is the SQUARE
of the Fibonacci transfer matrix!

T_F² = [[2, 1], [1, 1]] — NOT equal to T_B = [[3,-1],[1,0]]

Eigenvalue relationship:
  φ = 1.618034, φ² = 2.618034
  ψ = -0.618034, ψ² = 0.381966
  φ² + ψ² = 3.000000 = 3 (trace of T_B)
  φ² · ψ² = 1.000000 = 1 (det of T_B)

Verifying B_m(1) = F_p (p=2m+1):
  m=1, p=3: B_m(1) = 2, F_p = 2, match = True
  m=2, p=5: B_m(1) = 5, F_p = 5, match = True
  m=3, p=7: B_m(1) = 13, F_p = 13, match = True
  m=4, p=9: B_m(1) = 34, F_p = 34, match = True
  m=5, p=11: B_m(1) = 89, F_p = 89, match = True
  m=6, p=13: B_m(1) = 233, F_p = 233, match = True
  m=7, p=15: B_m(1) = 610, F_p = 610, match = True
  m=8, p=17: B_m(1) = 1597, F_p = 1597, match = True
  m=9, p=19: B_m(1) = 4181, F_p = 4181, match = True

======================================================================
PART 2: BINET FORMULA AND GALOIS SPLITTING OF prod(1+Q_k)
======================================================================

Galois structure: K = Q(cos 2π/p), [K:Q] = m = (p-1)/2

Q(√5) ⊂ K iff 5 is a quadratic residue mod p:
  p= 5: (5/p) = +0, Q(√5) ⊂ K: ramified
  p= 7: (5/p) = -1, Q(√5) ⊂ K: NO
  p=11: (5/p) = +1, Q(√5) ⊂ K: YES
  p=13: (5/p) = -1, Q(√5) ⊂ K: NO
  p=17: (5/p) = -1, Q(√5) ⊂ K: NO
  p=19: (5/p) = +1, Q(√5) ⊂ K: YES
  p=23: (5/p) = -1, Q(√5) ⊂ K: NO
  p=29: (5/p) = +1, Q(√5) ⊂ K: YES
  p=31: (5/p) = +1, Q(√5) ⊂ K: YES
  p=37: (5/p) = -1, Q(√5) ⊂ K: NO
  p=41: (5/p) = +1, Q(√5) ⊂ K: YES
  p=43: (5/p) = -1, Q(√5) ⊂ K: NO

By QR: (5/p) = (p/5). So Q(√5) ⊂ K iff p ≡ ±1 mod 5

Galois action on Q_k for Interval tournament:

