PART 5: B_m(x) AS LATTICE GAS PARTITION FUNCTION
======================================================================

CRUCIAL CONNECTION: Both H(T) and prod(1+Q_k) arise from
lattice gas / hard-core polymer models!

H(T) = I(Ω(T), 2) = hard-core lattice gas on odd-cycle graph at activity 2
prod(1+Q_k) = ???

Q: Can prod(1+Q_k) be written as a hard-core partition function too?

prod(1+Q_k) = I(empty graph on m vertices, with activities Q_k)
  = sum_{A ⊆ [m]} prod_{k∈A} Q_k

By contrast, H = I(Ω(T), 2) uses the ODD-CYCLE graph with uniform activity 2.

So the ratio H / prod(1+Q_k) compares:
  - Hard-core gas on Ω(T) vs no-exclusion gas on {Q_k}
  - The GRAPH STRUCTURE in Ω(T) excludes some configurations

  p=7: H(Int) = 175, prod(1+Q) = 13.0 = F_7 = 13
         H / F_p = 13.461538
         H / (p · F_p) = 1.923077
