======================================================================
SYNTHESIS: THE FIBONACCI-TOURNAMENT DICTIONARY (EXTENDED)
======================================================================

TIER 1 — PROVEN IDENTITIES:
  prod(1+Q_k) = F_p (Fibonacci number)
  prod(a+Q_k) = a^m · B_m(1/a) (Morgan-Voyce)
  B_m(x) = U_m(1+x/2) (Chebyshev of 2nd kind)
  B_m(1) = F_{2m+1} = F_p
  B_m(4) = Pell_{2m+1}
  T_B eigenvalues = φ², ψ² (golden ratio squared)
  CF: B_m/B_{m-1} = [3; 3, 3, ...] → φ² (periodic CF)

TIER 2 — STRUCTURAL PARALLELS:
  F_n = I(P_{n-2}, 1) — independent sets of path
  H(T) = I(Ω(T), 2) — independent sets of odd-cycle graph
  Both are lattice gas partition functions!
  Fibonacci: activity 1 on path graph
  Tournament: activity 2 on odd-cycle graph

TIER 3 — KEY QUESTIONS:
  Q1: Is there a graph homomorphism Ω(Int) → P_{p-2}?
  Q2: Does the cluster expansion of H/F_p have a nice form?
  Q3: Can the Binet splitting φ^p, ψ^p be matched to Galois orbits of Q_k?
  Q4: Does Cassini-type identity B_{m-1}·B_{m+1} - B_m² = (-1)^m
      have a tournament interpretation?

TIER 4 — PROOF STRATEGY:
  The path from Fibonacci to H-maximization goes:
  (1) Interval Q_k are zeros of B_m(1/x) (up to scaling)
  (2) B_m encodes the Chebyshev/Dirichlet kernel structure
  (3) The Q_k are maximally CONCENTRATED (largest max, smallest min)
  (4) This concentration → max additive energy E(S)
  (5) Max E(S) → max Walsh degree-4 terms → max H
  (6) The Fibonacci identity prod(1+Q_k) = F_p is a SHADOW
      of the deeper: Q_k structure determines H

